50|$|As {{alternatives}} to the integrated seatpost mentioned above, some seatposts merely have an aerodynamic shape that either matches {{the shape of the}} aero <b>seat</b> <b>tube</b> or is only not round above a certain point. In the case of aero <b>seat</b> <b>tubes,</b> {{there are a variety of}} clamping mechanisms for such seatposts that include pinch bolts and wedges.|$|R
50|$|The {{size of the}} {{seatpost}} {{is dependent}} upon the internal dimensions of the <b>seat</b> <b>tube</b> of the bicycle frame. They come in various diameters, lengths and offsets. Offset is {{the distance between the}} centerline of the seatpost tube, and the centerline of the clamp area. Shims are often available to adapt a too-small seatpost to a too-large <b>seat</b> <b>tube.</b>|$|R
50|$|The <b>seat</b> <b>tube</b> {{contains}} the seatpost of the bike, which {{connects to the}} saddle. The saddle height is adjustable by changing how far the seatpost is inserted into the <b>seat</b> <b>tube.</b> On some bikes, this is achieved using a quick release lever. The seatpost must be inserted at least a certain length; this is marked with a minimum insertion mark.|$|R
